01:05:30.920 --> 01:05:37.110
Senior English address, a
Harvard spring candidate

01:05:37.110 --> 01:05:41.518
for the degree of bachelor
of arts, Sarah Abushaar.

01:06:02.450 --> 01:06:06.660
When I was around seven,
my toothless brother

01:06:06.660 --> 01:06:11.900
and I on long, boring
taxi rides in Syria

01:06:11.900 --> 01:06:14.920
would indulge in
imperialistic fantasies

01:06:14.920 --> 01:06:18.740
of how we wanted to
take over the country

01:06:18.740 --> 01:06:21.360
outside our windows.

01:06:21.360 --> 01:06:24.830
My parents would quickly
crush these imperial conquests

01:06:24.830 --> 01:06:30.130
by warning, shh, you'll get
taking by Secret Service

01:06:30.130 --> 01:06:32.800
if they hear you.

01:06:32.800 --> 01:06:36.290
The walls everywhere,
we were told,

01:06:36.290 --> 01:06:39.850
could hear our
revolutionary ideas

01:06:39.850 --> 01:06:42.650
and would send us to prison.

01:06:42.650 --> 01:06:47.870
Whereas children here had
ghosts and the bogey man,

01:06:47.870 --> 01:06:53.270
our equivalents our governments.

01:06:53.270 --> 01:06:57.550
Fast forward to 2010.

01:06:57.550 --> 01:07:00.540
When I first got
here, someone told me

01:07:00.540 --> 01:07:05.037
if Harvard shut its gates, it
could be its own country, just

01:07:05.037 --> 01:07:05.745
like the Vatican.

01:07:09.800 --> 01:07:12.080
As I've walked through
this place every day

01:07:12.080 --> 01:07:14.750
for the past four
years, I was struck

01:07:14.750 --> 01:07:18.750
by how true this idea was.

01:07:18.750 --> 01:07:22.910
I thought everywhere
the Harvard nation.

01:07:22.910 --> 01:07:27.160
I saw it in the big
and obvious things.

01:07:27.160 --> 01:07:30.260
We had our own version of the
Statue of Liberty-- the John

01:07:30.260 --> 01:07:32.700
Harvard statue.

01:07:32.700 --> 01:07:39.160
Our own embassies, the Harvard
clubs of Boston and London.

01:07:39.160 --> 01:07:44.360
A tax collection agency, the
Harvard Alumni Association.

01:07:44.360 --> 01:07:48.970
[LAUGHTER]

01:07:48.970 --> 01:07:52.990
And an endowment larger than
more than half the world's

01:07:52.990 --> 01:07:56.150
countries GDPs.

01:07:56.150 --> 01:07:59.960
We also have our own
diplomatic passports.

01:07:59.960 --> 01:08:03.880
Nowhere did I see this
more clearly than at US

01:08:03.880 --> 01:08:07.690
immigration at
Boston Logan Airport.

01:08:07.690 --> 01:08:10.100
Whenever they saw I was
coming from the Middle

01:08:10.100 --> 01:08:12.690
East-- what were
you doing there.

01:08:12.690 --> 01:08:13.890
Why are you here?

01:08:13.890 --> 01:08:15.935
Why did God make you
from the Middle East?

01:08:19.540 --> 01:08:25.319
But I made sure I dressed like
our overly proud Harvard dads

01:08:25.319 --> 01:08:28.130
with Harvard hat, Harvard shirt,
Harvard shorts, and Harvard

01:08:28.130 --> 01:08:30.470
underwear.

01:08:30.470 --> 01:08:35.130
And as soon as they saw I
was a citizen of Harvard,

01:08:35.130 --> 01:08:38.750
oh, you go to Harvard.

01:08:38.750 --> 01:08:42.300
Surely you must not be a
national security threat.

01:08:42.300 --> 01:08:43.596
Welcome to America.

01:08:47.010 --> 01:08:53.420
And suddenly, all the gates to
the American dream opened wide.

01:08:56.710 --> 01:08:59.450
I saw it everywhere,
this Harvard nation,

01:08:59.450 --> 01:09:04.229
but I saw it not just
in the hard structures.

01:09:04.229 --> 01:09:09.689
But more importantly, in
its invisible institutions.

01:09:09.689 --> 01:09:13.840
The invisible scaffolds
around and under-girding

01:09:13.840 --> 01:09:16.660
the hard institutions.

01:09:16.660 --> 01:09:20.840
I saw it in the quarreling
columns of the Crimson

01:09:20.840 --> 01:09:26.290
newspaper, it's kung fu fights
of ideas and lively student

01:09:26.290 --> 01:09:31.569
debates with the potency
to propel policy changes

01:09:31.569 --> 01:09:35.069
by the next morning's print.

01:09:35.069 --> 01:09:39.779
I saw it in our cluttered
bulletin boards, bustling

01:09:39.779 --> 01:09:44.180
with life, with announcements
of student led conferences,

01:09:44.180 --> 01:09:46.670
Broadway worthy shows,
and dorm room projects

01:09:46.670 --> 01:09:49.220
turned world's next Facebook
smothering each other

01:09:49.220 --> 01:09:52.800
for our cursory glimpse.

01:09:52.800 --> 01:09:56.020
A trivial detail,
these cluttered boards

01:09:56.020 --> 01:09:58.900
that often slip notice.

01:09:58.900 --> 01:10:04.530
But where some saw papers, I saw
passions, purpose, creativity.

01:10:04.530 --> 01:10:11.060
I saw a heartbeat of civic
community's vivacity.

01:10:11.060 --> 01:10:12.780
My parents'
countries were places

01:10:12.780 --> 01:10:15.960
where institutional
dysfunction killed off

01:10:15.960 --> 01:10:18.690
the social dynamism and
vibrant productivity.

01:10:18.690 --> 01:10:22.750
And so I felt acutely
here the value

01:10:22.750 --> 01:10:29.340
of civil society and living,
breathing institutions.

01:10:32.020 --> 01:10:35.690
My time here would
give me a working model

01:10:35.690 --> 01:10:37.630
of a better world.

01:10:37.630 --> 01:10:44.660
Not only that, but that sense of
empowerment to initiate change.

01:10:44.660 --> 01:10:48.400
You see, with those
spying walls still lurking

01:10:48.400 --> 01:10:52.140
in my memory that constrained
the little Napoleons

01:10:52.140 --> 01:10:56.060
in my brother and me, you
might imagine my shock

01:10:56.060 --> 01:10:58.680
when in one of my
first classes here,

01:10:58.680 --> 01:11:04.143
I suddenly found myself
debating a president.

01:11:09.720 --> 01:11:11.150
So it's the 1990s.

01:11:11.150 --> 01:11:14.140
Our negotiations class
professor set the stage.

01:11:14.140 --> 01:11:17.440
A war is about to break out
between Ecuador and Peru.

01:11:17.440 --> 01:11:19.340
How will you stop it?

01:11:19.340 --> 01:11:21.850
I raised my hand to respond.

01:11:21.850 --> 01:11:22.590
Wait.

01:11:22.590 --> 01:11:25.410
Professor Shapiro stopped me.

01:11:25.410 --> 01:11:28.330
Tell the president what to do.

01:11:28.330 --> 01:11:31.563
And in walked the
Ecuadorian president.

01:11:35.070 --> 01:11:38.260
And bringing the
president to me and having

01:11:38.260 --> 01:11:40.800
me speak to and question
a shaper of history

01:11:40.800 --> 01:11:45.400
and experience the
value he saw in my view,

01:11:45.400 --> 01:11:47.770
Harvard would make me
feel I too could be him.

01:11:47.770 --> 01:11:50.480
I too had the power to
shape history and not

01:11:50.480 --> 01:11:53.350
just be passively shaped by it.

01:11:53.350 --> 01:11:55.840
That sense of
infinite possibility

01:11:55.840 --> 01:12:01.120
we have as children to think
big and conquer great things

01:12:01.120 --> 01:12:04.180
was returned to me here.

01:12:04.180 --> 01:12:07.810
A less despotic version of it.

01:12:07.810 --> 01:12:12.630
But what seemed intractable
problems of the world

01:12:12.630 --> 01:12:19.980
became opportunities for
me, for us to change things.

01:12:19.980 --> 01:12:23.500
You know, when I first got
here, my name was Sarah.

01:12:23.500 --> 01:12:25.343
After Harvard, it
would become, hey

01:12:25.343 --> 01:12:30.590
Harvard, with people
stuffing 378 years,

01:12:30.590 --> 01:12:34.600
5,000 acres of real estate, the
entirety of Widener Library,

01:12:34.600 --> 01:12:41.700
and 32 heads of state all into
my five foot six inch self.

01:12:41.700 --> 01:12:50.270
Ridiculous as it is, there's
a strange reality to it.

01:12:50.270 --> 01:12:52.930
Arab American
author Randa Jarrar

01:12:52.930 --> 01:12:56.330
pictures inhabiting a new
place as running barefoot,

01:12:56.330 --> 01:12:58.610
the skin of our
feet collecting sand

01:12:58.610 --> 01:13:01.250
and seeds and rocks and
grass until we had shoes,

01:13:01.250 --> 01:13:06.350
shoes made of everything
we picked up as we ran.

01:13:06.350 --> 01:13:10.040
And running through Harvard
Yard over the past four years,

01:13:10.040 --> 01:13:14.950
the skin of our feet collecting
a world of experiences,

01:13:14.950 --> 01:13:21.110
we each become this
place in a strange way.

01:13:21.110 --> 01:13:24.190
Each of us picking up bits of
people, and history, and ideas

01:13:24.190 --> 01:13:27.560
that changed the way
we saw the world.

01:13:27.560 --> 01:13:33.230
Accumulations I hope we will
continue to wear on our souls

01:13:33.230 --> 01:13:37.360
and leave a footprint of all the
best we took from Harvard Yard

01:13:37.360 --> 01:13:40.300
on our new destinations.

01:13:40.300 --> 01:13:45.090
And that's why I am
hopeful for the future.

01:13:45.090 --> 01:13:47.750
I'm hopeful because of
my dining hall dinners

01:13:47.750 --> 01:13:50.560
spent marveling at friends who,
while their countries waged

01:13:50.560 --> 01:13:53.910
bloody war against each
other, are able to carry out

01:13:53.910 --> 01:13:58.830
civil conversation and build
generative projects together.

01:13:58.830 --> 01:14:01.770
I am hopeful because
of the founding mothers

01:14:01.770 --> 01:14:05.530
and founding fathers of
revolutionary ideas like these

01:14:05.530 --> 01:14:07.735
being launched
into the world, who

01:14:07.735 --> 01:14:10.050
will make of its institutions,
its constitutions,

01:14:10.050 --> 01:14:16.010
its hospitals, its art
houses something better.

01:14:16.010 --> 01:14:21.590
We hear a lot in the news
about an Arab Spring.

01:14:21.590 --> 01:14:26.690
This graduation is
sending 6,000 revolutions

01:14:26.690 --> 01:14:30.450
into the world in the 6,000
revolutions graduating

01:14:30.450 --> 01:14:34.460
as part of the class of 2014.

01:14:34.460 --> 01:14:38.090
If we take those revolutions,
those great ideas

01:14:38.090 --> 01:14:41.910
sparked behind Chipotle
burritos and Starbucks coffee

01:14:41.910 --> 01:14:46.660
cups in our version of Tahrir
Square, Harvard Square,

01:14:46.660 --> 01:14:50.480
out with us into the real world,
into the real Tahrir Squares,

01:14:50.480 --> 01:14:52.610
and make something of them.

01:14:52.610 --> 01:14:55.100
Revolution's not in
arms, but in minds

01:14:55.100 --> 01:15:01.500
more powerful, and
permanent, and pervasive.

01:15:01.500 --> 01:15:09.220
For this isn't a Ukrainian
revolution or an Arab Spring,

01:15:09.220 --> 01:15:13.340
but a global revolution.

01:15:13.340 --> 01:15:17.840
This is the Harvard
spring of 2014.

01:15:17.840 --> 01:15:23.340
This is the Harvard Spring.

01:15:23.340 --> 01:15:26.590
