landmark commission

02:08:03.370 --> 02:08:07.240
on protecting human subjects
of biomedical research,

02:08:07.240 --> 02:08:13.350
she played a formative role in
shaping the field of bioethics.

02:08:13.350 --> 02:08:18.740
Over the years, she has applied
her expertise and judgment

02:08:18.740 --> 02:08:21.820
to complex ethical questions
posed by everything

02:08:21.820 --> 02:08:25.940
from human radiation
experiments to genomics,

02:08:25.940 --> 02:08:30.560
from stem cell research to
the interplay of bioethics

02:08:30.560 --> 02:08:32.540
and race.

02:08:32.540 --> 02:08:36.570
At Harvard, she brought
her strong moral compass,

02:08:36.570 --> 02:08:40.970
her multi-disciplinary
outlook, and her deep concern

02:08:40.970 --> 02:08:45.030
for educational opportunity to
bear on the work of the Harvard

02:08:45.030 --> 02:08:51.040
Corporation from
2006 until 2012.

02:08:51.040 --> 02:08:53.290
She has also played
leadership roles

02:08:53.290 --> 02:08:56.590
on the boards of Wheaton
College, the Russell Sage

02:08:56.590 --> 02:09:00.520
Foundation, and the
Kaiser Family Foundation,

02:09:00.520 --> 02:09:03.010
besides serving on
major advisory counsels

02:09:03.010 --> 02:09:04.880
for the National
Institutes of Health,

02:09:04.880 --> 02:09:07.360
the Institute of
Medicine, and others.

02:09:10.200 --> 02:09:13.370
She wears her prodigious
accomplishments

02:09:13.370 --> 02:09:16.930
with humility and grace.

02:09:16.930 --> 02:09:22.670
