02:10:25.550 --> 02:10:30.220
As a student, he was struck by
the incongruities he perceived

02:10:30.220 --> 02:10:34.400
between the standard models
taught in economics class

02:10:34.400 --> 02:10:38.360
and the realities he
witnessed in daily life.

02:10:38.360 --> 02:10:41.380
He began to question
the invisible hand

02:10:41.380 --> 02:10:45.250
and to wonder about
the limits of markets.

02:10:45.250 --> 02:10:48.680
In time, he rose to
prominence in an array

02:10:48.680 --> 02:10:52.230
of domains of economics--
macroeconomics

02:10:52.230 --> 02:10:57.550
and monetary theory,
development economics and trade,

02:10:57.550 --> 02:11:02.540
and the distribution of income
and wealth, to name a few.

02:11:02.540 --> 02:11:05.110
Among his academic
colleagues, he

02:11:05.110 --> 02:11:08.190
is perhaps best
recognized for shaping

02:11:08.190 --> 02:11:13.090
the economics of
information, in particular

02:11:13.090 --> 02:11:16.560
for explaining how uneven
access to information

02:11:16.560 --> 02:11:20.010
affects the
operation of markets.

02:11:20.010 --> 02:11:25.600
His work earned him a
Nobel Prize in 2001.

02:11:25.600 --> 02:11:28.100
His noted books
for wider audiences

02:11:28.100 --> 02:11:31.860
include Globalization
and its Discontents

02:11:31.860 --> 02:11:35.090
and The Price of Inequality.

02:11:35.090 --> 02:11:39.790
They reflect his concern for
how and when governments should

02:11:39.790 --> 02:11:42.530
intervene in markets,
and how efforts

02:11:42.530 --> 02:11:44.950
to spur the global
economy might be

02:11:44.950 --> 02:11:49.110
devised to lessen rather
than widen the growing

02:11:49.110 --> 02:11:53.890
gap between rich and poor.

02:11:53.890 --> 02:12:01.160
He served at MIT, Yale,
Stanford, Oxford, and Princeton

02:12:01.160 --> 02:12:03.910
before becoming a
university professor

02:12:03.910 --> 02:12:07.850
at Columbia, where he founded
the initiative for policy

02:12:07.850 --> 02:12:13.790
dialogue and co-chairs the
Committee on Global Thought.

02:12:13.790 --> 02:12:18.910
Deeply engaged with national and
international economic policy,

02:12:18.910 --> 02:12:22.830
he has also serve as chairman
of the President's Council

02:12:22.830 --> 02:12:28.220
of Economic Advisers, chief
economist of the World Bank,

02:12:28.220 --> 02:12:32.810
and chair of the UN commission
on reforming the International

02:12:32.810 --> 02:12:37.190
Monetary and Financial System.

02:12:37.190 --> 02:12:42.330
We recognize the eminent
economist Joseph Stiglitz.

02:12:42.330 --> 02:12:45.300
[APPLAUSE]

02:12:59.170 --> 02:13:05.850
Demarking the limits of markets,
discerning global discontents,

02:13:05.850 --> 02:13:10.560
a paramount progenitor
of information economics

02:13:10.560 --> 02:13:15.470
who bestrides the spheres
of theory and policy,

02:13:15.470 --> 02:13:19.120
Joseph E Stiglitz,
Doctor of Laws.

